data.name: label3.Text
data.value:
The beginning of the game, the stones are placed on the dark squares of the board. Progress is only on these slots, only forward, and only diagonally. The one player's stones are placed in the first three rows of the board, while the other player's stones are placed in the same way on his side. The player set in the settings window makes the first move. Each player in turn moves a playing stone from one dark square to a dark square in the opposite direction, diagonally. When a player clicks on a particular disc, he is shown the possible moves for that disc on the relevant squares (marked with red). A "skipping" of the opponent's stone (or "eating") is performed when a game disc is placed in a square adjacent to the opponent's disk, and the opponent's disk has a free slot. The skipping is performed by placing the disc in the free space over the opponent's stone, and removing the opponent's stone from the board. When a game disc reaches the last line (ie, the opponent's first), it becomes "king". A king is marked by a playing stone and a painting of a king over it. Unlike a regular stone, a king can move in all directions, that is, backward (diagonally), including "eating." Like any stone game, the opponent can skip the king and download him from the board. When there is a possibility to eat, it is necessary to do so. If there is more than one option to eat the player can choose the desired option. The game ends in victory, when one of the players has no stones left on the board, or when he has nothing to move his remaining pieces, because all his stones are blocked in all directions - at this moment, the player is declared with the largest number of discs and the game is over.
Successfully!
